Introduction

These series of articles are sort of what I believe what my parents would have liked to have known as they came to the United States in regards to finance. These articles are blanket solutions to family finance and are meant to help you build a foundation which would be required in terms of financial knowledge as you accumulate more wealth. However, I do strongly believe that a simple blanket solution is magnitudes more helpful than not having any solution at all.

Unfortunately, when it comes to finance Ive noticed that there is a knowledge gap between families earning lower income compared with families earning higher income. As you accumulate more wealth (time goes by typically families tend to grow financially) you will start to look towards how to manage your money. It just so happens that new knowledge in regards to wealth management starts to appear and you then make decisions based on this new found knowledge. However, the key mathematical concepts are equivalent no matter whether your making 30K or 300K. In this article I will be discussing the power of compound interest. And why no matter what your income is you should be stowing away a little bit of that income to go towards your retirement. Ill show you graphically how saving small contributions now end up adding years of income when it comes time to retirement.

The Equations

\[ \text{Portfolio Value} = \Sigma_{i=1}^{i=T} p_i(1+\frac{r}{n})^{n} + c\] \[ p = \text{principal}\] \[ r = \text{rate of growth}\] \[ c = \text{contributions} \] \[ n = \text{periods of compounding}\]

A brief summary into the math is that the portfolio is valued by summing up the growth and adding a yearly contribution for the next growth period. \(p_i\) in this case is the principal value (or that periods current portfolio value) which wouldve compounded at the rate of growth r. c is the contributions chosen made for each period n which we have assumed as 1-year.

Visualization

There are two graphs below. The first is a generic graph where you can control the amount of money you contribute a year, what rate that money grows at, and the number of years it is invested over (idealy till you feel comfortable enough to see a professional). Looking at the past 25 years, we see that the S&P500 has on average returned about 8.5%. I set the slider at 7% just to be conservative, you can play around with the slider scales for all and hover your mouse over the plot to see what the actual dollar values would accumulate to. This is a general graph not specifically invested in the market.

The second graph is more interesting and shows what would have happened if you had invested $1000 each year (roughly $83 a month) in the market over the last 25 years. The possible investments Ive made available are the ETFS (Exchange Traded Funds) SPY, QQQ, and DIA (representing the S&P500, Nasdaq, and Dow Jones Industrials). These are the most common ETFs that represent the overall US economy. Its clear no matter which ETF you invested in the results are great. These are the macro benchmarks firms/portfolio managers etc. all try to beat. When people say invest in the market these are the ETFs they are refering to.

Note: You want to make sure the weights roughly add to 1 as it represents the percentage value of that ETF making up your portfolio.
